    <title>Combined summary - BIP32/43-based standard for Schnorr signatures &amp; decentralized identity</title>
    <updated>2023-06-14T17:24:37.888104+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-February/018402.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In the world of blockchain technology, a significant concern is the issue of key reuse. This issue was discussed in an email conversation between Pieter and Maxim, where they talked about the need for a dedicated purpose or BIP to avoid key reuse for single-key pay-to-taproot and multisig participation. They agreed that using a distinct hardened derivation step for each would maintain provable security for both ECDSA and BIP340.Maxim suggested simplifying the process by having a dedicated deterministically-derived hardened key for each use case under a single standard. Still, Pieter pointed out that this proposal doesn't address the problem of preventing key reuse in multiple distinct groups of multisig sets. To solve this issue, Maxim proposes adding a new purpose field that supports hardened derivation for multisigs, single-sigs, etc. The BIP proposal includes a solution on how multisigs can be created in a simple and deterministic way without key reuse.Greg Maxwell notes that reusing keys for both ECDSA and BIP340 could potentially leak private keys, but this isn't a concern for Bitcoin transaction signing because the sighash indirectly commits to BIP341 or not, making it impossible to construct colliding messages.Apart from the discussion on key reuse, there was a proposal for a decentralized identity standard suitable for cypherpunk needs. The proposal focuses on revocation of identity scopes and full identities, allowing users to revoke specific scoped identities or completely revoke an identity without providing a new scope. It also includes layer-2 and 3 solutions that give users the ability to provide identity meta-information with features like decentralized non-blockchain database and search engine for metadata, partial meta-information disclosures, and multiple IDs under a root ID.Dr. Maxim Orlovsky received a message from Christopher Allen expressing his interest in supporting discussion and implementation on the topic they had previously discussed. Some patrons of Blockchain Commons may also be willing to financially support reference code related to decentralized identifiers.Lastly, in an email exchange between Dmitry and Maxim, they discussed the hardening of the testnet path for a proposed project. While Maxim suggested an unhardened testnet path, Dmitry argued that requiring privkey access to hardened paths in test software is acceptable because this behavior is expected in production. Ultimately, they agreed to change the "purpose" part of the path while leaving the rest unchanged to ensure better robustness.</summary>
